Here's a JavaScript function that takes an array of 5 numbers as input, checks if any of the numbers are prime, and prints the prime numbers to the console:

```javascript
function isPrime(num) {
  if (num <= 1) {
    return false;
  }
  for (let i = 2; i <= Math.sqrt(num); i++) {
    if (num % i === 0) {
      return false;
    }
  }
  return true;
}

function checkPrimes(numbers) {
  if (numbers.length !== 5) {
    console.error("Input array must contain exactly 5 numbers.");
    return;
  }

  for (let i = 0; i < numbers.length; i++) {
    if (isPrime(numbers[i])) {
      console.log(numbers[i]);
    }
  }
}

// Example usage:
const numbers = [2, 4, 5, 10, 13];
checkPrimes(numbers);
```

This code defines two functions: `isPrime` to check if a number is prime, and `checkPrimes` to iterate through the input array and print the prime numbers. The `isPrime` function uses a simple algorithm to check if a number is divisible by any integer between 2 and its square root.

